hobia Is Really a Public Service"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"Thank You, Duggars, Your Homophobia Is Really a Public Service"},"email_title":"Thank%20You%2C%20Duggars%2C%20Your%20Homophobia%20Is%20Really%20a%20Public%20Service%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"Thank%20You%2C%20Duggars%2C%20Your%20Homophobia%20Is%20Really%20a%20Public%20Service%0A%0AWhen%20gay%20marriage%20is%20passing%20in%20state%20after%20state%2C%20it%E2%80%99s%20easy%20to%20forget%20that%20not%20everyone%20is%20on%20the%20bandwagon%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3599721%2Fmichelle-duggar-homophobia-gay-rights%2F","omniture":{"modules":"rr-outbrain|rr-partner|rr-mag|rr-ad|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3599721\/michelle-duggar-homophobia-gay-rights\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3599400\/cosby-rape-black-icons\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/wp.me\/p5HMd-f6mQ","title":"How Herman Cain and President Obama Brought Down Bill Cosby","friendly_title":"How Herman Cain and President Obama Brought Down Bill Cosby","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"How Herman Cain and President Obama Brought Down Bill Cosby","contributor":true,"excerpt":"The allegations have been around for years. But we're only now willing to judge black icons like everybody else.","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 21, 2014","published":"2014-11-21 11:18:07","updated":"2014-11-21 16:18:07","minute":"11:18 am","short":"11\/21"},"authors":[{"id":211864947,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/john-mcwhorter\/","name":"John McWhorter","bio":"","short_bio":"John McWhorter is an associate professor of English and comparative literature at Columbia University.","types":["contributor"],"twitter":"","twitter_url":"","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"http:\/\/i2.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/01\/s5z988821.jpg?crop=50px%2C0px%2C234px%2C234px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":true}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-outbrain\" data-name=\"rr-outbrain\"><div class=\"OUTBRAIN\" data-src=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3599400\/cosby-rape-black-icons\/\" data-widget-id=\"SB_2\" data-ob-template=\"timemag\"><\/div><\/aside><p>With the curtain falling on Bill Cosby&rsquo;s career in the wake of multiple accusations of his raping women throughout his career, many have asked why it took so long for America to condemn the man. This seam in his past has been aired quite often over the past 10 years, and yet his iconic status as America&rsquo;s favorite (black) Dad has continued, with NBC having even been readying to build yet another sitcom around him until this Wednesday. What is it about <em>now<\/em> that is making us &mdash; white, black and other &mdash; see Cosby plain?<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-partner\" data-name=\"rr-partner\"><div class=\"read-more-list\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3599394\/bill-cosby-accusers-cosby-show-fans\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">Ask an Ethicist: Can I Still Watch The Cosby Show?<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3599950\/intersex-meaning\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">This is What Intersex Means<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/storyline\/michael-brown-shooting\/pair-suspected-trying-acquire-bombs-ferguson-protests-n254021?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Feds Suspect Pair Sought Bombs for Ferguson Protests <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/crime-courts\/ohio-men-wrongly-convicted-murder-after-39-years-released-n253356?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Two Ohio Men Wrongly Convicted of Murder Walk Free <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/us-news\/fsu-shooter-myron-may-left-message-i-do-not-want-n253436?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">FSU Shooter Left Message: 'I Do Not Want to Die in Vain' <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>Partly, Barack Obama and Herman Cain.<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-mag\" data-name=\"rr-mag\"><div class=\"read-more-inline magazine has-cover\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h read-more-popular\">Popular Among Subscribers<\/h6>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"popular-lead\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547827\/the-art-of-science\/?pcd=pw-pas\"><img src=\"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/10\/timeinterstellarcover.jpg?w=560\" alt=\"\" title=\"\" data-loaded=\"true\"><\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547827\/the-art-of-science\/?pcd=pw-pas\" class=\"read-more-article\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title time-icons time-icons-key\"><em>Interstellar<\/em>, Where No Movie Has Gone Before<\/h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https:\/\/subscription.time.com\/storefront\/subscribe-to-time\/link\/1019509.html\" class=\"subscribe-button\">Subscribe<\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547825\/nucor-tries-to-reverse-decline-in-american-steelmaking\/?pcd=pw-pas\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title time-icons time-icons-key\">The Last Men of Steel<\/h3><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3547828\/review-interstellar-christopher-nolan\/?pcd=pw-pas\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title time-icons time-icons-key\">Review: <em>Interstellar\u2019s<\/em> Wonder of Worlds Beyond<\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>Of course, two other factors, more apparent, have played a role &mdash; but alone, they would not have popped the lock.<\/p>\n<p>For one, Cosby has alienated many black people with his criticisms of black behavior, crystallized in the now famous &ldquo;Pound Cake speech&rdquo; of 2004 commemorating <em>Brown v. the Board of Education<\/em>. When black comedian Hannibal Buress <a href=\"http:\/\/www.vulture.com\/2014\/10\/hannibal-buress-called-bill-cosby-a-rapist.html\" target=\"_blank\">charged<\/a> that Cosby is a racist, sparking the latest events when the clip went viral, Buress was explicit that it rankles him that Cosby has called for black people to &ldquo;Pull your pants up,&rdquo; etc. when Cosby himself had, shall we say, not done so.<\/p>\n<p>Yet, the dirt on Cosby had been aired far and wide soon after the Pound Cake speech, with black author and pundit Michael Eric Dyson even covering the territory in his 2005 <a href=\"http:\/\/www.amazon.com\/Bill-Cosby-Right-Black-Middle\/dp\/0465017207\/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1416532330&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=is+bill+cosby+right\">book<\/a>, a broadside against Cosby&rsquo;s cultural opinions. Newsweek, The Today Show, People, and other sources chimed in around the same time. No one remotely interested in Cosby could have missed the charges, and while today Twitter and Facebook get things around especially quickly, by 2005 and 2006 broadband and blogs were already influencing opinion at a dizzying rate. Irritation over Cosby&rsquo;s views alone, then, did not threaten his iconic status &mdash; especially given that more black people than often acknowledged actually concur with Cosby&rsquo;s cultural opinions.<\/p>\n<p>The second factor in why Cosby has been outed now &mdash; one that is key, but not decisive &mdash; is that sexual violation of women has been so widely discussed in America over the past few years. The &ldquo;legitimate rape&rdquo; conceptions of congressman Todd Akin and today&rsquo;s calls for universities to address the frequency of rape on their campuses have made it much less likely that Cosby&rsquo;s behavior could be given a pass.<\/p>\n<p>But even this doesn&rsquo;t fully answer the &ldquo;Why now?&rdquo; question. Enlightened American sensibilities about rape have not taken a quantum leap since, say, 2005. The major dividing line for that would be in the early &#8217;90s, when sexual harassment and date rape entered mainstream discussion and forever banished the old-time Mad Men idea that such things were a mere matter of some men being &ldquo;all hands.&rdquo; Who by 2005, upon hearing about what Cosby did, was thinking &ldquo;Oh well, boys will be boys!&rdquo;?<\/p>\n<p>We get closer to truth in Rebecca Traister&rsquo;s <a href=\"http:\/\/www.newrepublic.com\/article\/120338\/bill-cosby-rape-allegations-why-america-took-so-long-wake\">point<\/a> that America has been afraid to condemn Cosby out of a sense that it would be almost sacrilegious to pull down such an iconic representation of blackness. More specifically, whites have given him a pass out of a sense that it would be racist not to, while blacks have been reluctant to assist in the defrocking of such a beloved figure, chary of aiding and abetting whites in racist dismissal of black achievement and authority.<\/p>\n<p>What has made the difference is that certain happenings of late have let America make a particular kind of post-Civil Rights adjustment: getting past the polite fiction that all criticisms of a black person are racist, and if not overtly then &ldquo;on a certain level.&rdquo;<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3599400\"><\/div>\n<p>Namely here is where Cain and Obama come in. The implosion of Herman Cain&rsquo;s quest for the Republican nomination in 2011 in the wake of charges (from white women) of sexual harassment and infidelity was a handy transition. Cain&rsquo;s Republican politics and jolly dismissal of traditional Civil Rights positions meant that few blacks were primed to dismiss the accusations against him as racist, as a &ldquo;lynching,&rdquo; and so on. Instead, we simply saw Cain as a man brought down for proper reasons, his color beside the point.<\/p>\n<p>It probably had to be a black Republican that this happened to. But since then, a consensus has settled in on the question as to how much of a part racism plays in the animus of those who dislike President Obama. And the verdict is: racism does play some part. But still, only ideologues think racism is the only reason, or even close to the only reason, someone might not be crazy about Obama&rsquo;s performance in the Oval Office.<\/p>\n<p>At best, Obama is likely to go down as having been an OK President, and in grappling with that, Blue America has gotten a quiet lesson in evaluating black people according to the content of their character &mdash; despite having thought they already did that by voting for him in the first place.<\/p>\n<p>Hence a moment when it is newly easy to see Cosby not as a Black Gentleman With Some Issues but as a man, period, with some serious moral flaws, deserving no more &ldquo;understanding&rdquo; about it than Senator Bob Packwood did about his related tendencies. Meanwhile, black America, having seen that in our times the public can turn on, or trenchantly criticize, a black public figure without igniting a general backlash against black achievement, is less likely to circle the wagons around someone like Cosby than it formerly would have been.<\/p>\n<p>What stings about Cosby is that someone with his warm humor and furious commitment to uplift could at the same time have such a pitilessly abusive take on women and sex. It&rsquo;s like finding this out about your Dad, or certainly for me. Cosby and my own father were both working-class black men of a certain Philadelphia generation, and there was even a commonality of demeanor; my father was funny in the exact same way as Cosby, and danced just like Cosby did in the credits of the Cosby Show.<\/p>\n<p>But Dad didn&rsquo;t rape women. The lesson is that that kind of evil can lurk in the hearts of any kind of man, and we need to watch for it and call it out when it turns up to dissuade its survival in our civilization. And this time we&rsquo;re learning it not from A Black Man, but from someone we, in a way, honor by treating as just a man. Weirdly, this is a kind of progress.<\/p>\n<div class=\"newsletter-shortcode the-brief\">\n<form action=\"https:\/\/ebm.cheetahmail.com\/r\/regf2\" method=\"post\" target=\"time_brief_popup\" onsubmit=\"window.open(this.action, 'time_brief_popup', 'width=486,height=250');\">\n    <label class=\"intro\"><small>Sign Up for<\/small> <span class=\"no-wrap\">THE <strong class=\"time-red\">BRIEF<\/strong><\/span> <small class=\"and-more\">and more<\/small> <small class=\"example\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/newsletter\/the-brief\/\" target=\"_blank\">view example<\/a><\/small><\/label>\n    <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"n\" value=\"4\">\n    <input name=\"aid\" type=\"hidden\" value=\"1078532063\">\n    <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"fsub\" value=\"2095224265\">\n    <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"TIME_SOURCE\" value=\"shortcode_thebrief\">\n    <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"re\" value=\"http:\/\/f.time.chtah.net\/i\/30\/1078532063\/thanks.html\">\n    <input type=\"text\" class=\"text input-field email\" name=\"email\" placeholder=\"Email\">\n    <input type=\"submit\" class=\"submit button\" value=\"Submit\">\n<small class=\"example after\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/newsletter\/the-brief\/\" target=\"_blank\">view example<\/a><\/small>\n<\/form>\n<\/div>\n<p><em>Read next: <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3598207\/bill-cosby-rape-accusations-silence\/?xid=time_readnext\" target=\"_blank\">Bill Cosby, Camille Cosby and the Oppressive Power of Silence<\/a><\/em><\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3599400\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=How%20Herman%20Cain%20and%20President%20Obama%20Brought%20Down%20Bill%20Cosby%20%7C%20TIME&body=How%20Herman%20Cain%20and%20President%20Obama%20Brought%20Down%20Bill%20Cosby%0A%0AThe%20allegations%20have%20been%20around%20for%20years.%20But%20we%27re%20only%20now%20willing%20to%20judge%20black%20icons%20like%20everybody%20else.%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3599400%2Fcosby-rape-black-icons%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3599400%2Fcosby-rape-black-icons%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f6mQ&text=John%20McWhorter%3A%20Why%20we%27re%20just%20now%20willing%20to%20judge%20Bill%20Cosby%E2%80%94a%20black%20icon%E2%80%94like%20anyone%20else%3A&via=TIMEIdeas\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3599400%2Fcosby-rape-black-icons%2F&title=How+Herman+Cain+and+President+Obama+Brought+Down+Bill+Cosby\" data-event=\"linkedin\" title=\"Click to post this article to LinkedIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\"3599400\" data-url=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3599400\/cosby-rape-black-icons\/\" data-title=\"How Herman Cain and President Obama Brought Down Bill Cosby\" title=\"Click to view and post comments\" data-event=\"comment-click\">0<\/a>\n<\/span>\n<\/aside>","section":{"name":"Ideas","slug":"ideas","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/ideas\/","description":"TIME Ideas hosts the world's leading voices, providing commentary and expertise on the most compelling events in news, society, and culture. We welcome outside contributions. To submit a piece, email ideas@time.com."},"tag":{"name":"Culture","slug":"culture","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/culture\/"},"tags":"Culture","hero":{"class":"landscape","thumbnail":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/bilss-cosby-1.jpg?w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/bilss-cosby-1.jpg?w=280","small_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/bilss-cosby-1.jpg?w=560","large":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/bilss-cosby-1.jpg?w=550","large_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/bilss-cosby-1.jpg?w=1100"},"credit":"Lucas Jackson\u2014Reuters","caption":"Bill Cosby in New York in 2011. ","alt":"Actor Bill Cosby in New York in 2011.","providers":[]},"id":3599400,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3599400%2Fcosby-rape-black-icons%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-f6mQ","encoded_title":"How+Herman+Cain+and+President+Obama+Brought+Down+Bill+Cosby","twitter_text":"John%20McWhorter%3A%20Why%20we%27re%20just%20now%20willing%20to%20judge%20Bill%20Cosby%E2%80%94a%20black%20icon%E2%80%94like%20anyone%20else%3A","twitter_via":"TIMEIdeas","subjects":[null],"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"How Herman Cain and President Obama Brought Down Bill Cosby"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"How Herman Cain and President Obama Brought Down Bill Cosby"},"email_title":"How%20Herman%20Cain%20and%20President%20Obama%20Brought%20Down%20Bill%20Cosby%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"How%20Herman%20Cain%20and%20President%20Obama%20Brought%20Down%20Bill%20Cosby%0A%0AThe%20allegations%20have%20been%20around%20for%20years.%20But%20we%27re%20only%20now%20willing%20to%20judge%20black%20icons%20like%20everybody%20else.%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3599400%2Fcosby-rape-black-icons%2F","omniture":{"modules":"rr-outbrain|rr-partner|rr-mag|rr-ad|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3599400\/cosby-rape-black-icons\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3598437\/charles-manson-supreme-court-gay-marriage\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/wp.me\/p5HMd-f67j","title":"Prop. 8 Plaintiffs: Charles Manson Can Get Married, But We Still Can&#8217;t","friendly_title":"Prop. 8 Plaintiffs: Charles Manson Can Get Married, But We Still Can\u2019t","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"Prop. 8 Plaintiffs: Charles Manson Can Get Married, But We Still Can&#8217;t","contributor":true,"excerpt":"By not ruling on marriage equality, murderers are afforded more fairness and dignity than our LGBT brothers and sisters","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 21, 2014","published":"2014-11-21 09:14:51","updated":"2014-11-21 14:14:51","minute":"9:14 am","short":"11\/21"},"authors":[{"id":305295939,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/jeff-zarrillo-and-paul-katami\/","name":"Jeff Zarrillo and Paul Katami","bio":"<em>Jeff Zarrillo and Paul Katami were plaintiffs in the landmark Supreme Court decision in the federal lawsuit against Proposition 8 in California.<\/em>","short_bio":"","types":{"120280":"contributor"},"twitter":"","twitter_url":"","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":null,"contributor":true}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-outbrain\" data-name=\"rr-outbrain\"><div class=\"OUTBRAIN\" data-src=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3598437\/charles-manson-supreme-court-gay-marriage\/\" data-widget-id=\"SB_2\" data-ob-template=\"timemag\"><\/div><\/aside><p>When the news broke that Charles Manson had obtained a marriage license while serving out his life sentence in a California prison, we were mad. Really mad. This man was sentenced to death&mdash;a sentence later commuted to life in prison&mdash;after being found guilty of conspiracy to commit mass murder. The Supreme Court has told him that his right to marry is federally protected. That same court has yet to affirm that same right for the LGBT community. The only thing we are guilty of is falling in love with a member of the same sex.<\/p>\n<p>So while Manson and his bride-to-be make their wedding plans, thousands upon thousands of LGBT couples in 15 states, which accounts for nearly 30% of the U.S. population, are left at the altar. Opponents of marriage equality surely can&rsquo;t say that Manson is more worthy of the right to marry than the couples in these states, can they? Would Family Research Council&rsquo;s Tony Perkins rather have a dinner in our loving home or in the jailhouse cafeteria with a man who has no regard for human life? Would Cardinal Timothy Dolan prefer Manson and his &ldquo;Helter Skelter&rdquo; cult to the God and churches that many good and decent LGBT couples pray at and want to be married in? Would National Organization for Marriage&rsquo;s Brian Brown prefer the sanctity of this sham Manson marriage&ndash;to a woman he is not even permitted to have a child with&ndash;over the marriage of loving and committed gay couples who are already raising children?<\/p>\n<p>Our society is affording prison inmates more fairness and dignity than that of our LGBT brothers and sisters. Ted Olson and David Boies, who were our attorneys in the Prop 8 case, underscored this dichotomy to Chief Judge Vaughn Walker in court when fighting for our right to marry. Frankly, we don&rsquo;t care if Manson gets married. It&rsquo;s his right. Good for him. What we can&rsquo;t stand by and tolerate is inaction by the Supreme Court on this issue. The piecemeal approach with which the Court has &ldquo;ruled&rdquo; in favor of marriage equality&ndash;by not ruling on the issue&ndash;is not nearly enough. Now that the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals has affirmed the right for states within its jurisdiction to discriminate against its LGBT citizens by preventing them to marry the person they love, the Supreme Court must agree to hear one or all of the cases and do the right thing. You did it for Manson and now the prison has assigned him a wedding coordinator. We plan great weddings. What about us?<\/p>\n